## 🔄 Transaction Rollback Scenarios

### Scenario 1: Insufficient Stock

```java
@Transactional
public void createOrder() {
    // Start transaction
    
    Order order = new Order();
    orderRepository.save(order); // Saved to DB
    
    // Try to deduct inventory
    inventoryService.deductInventory(productId, 1000); 
    // Throws InsufficientStockException
    
    // Transaction rolls back
    // Order is NOT saved (rollback)
}
```

**Result:** No changes persisted, database remains consistent

---

### Scenario 2: Database Constraint Violation

```java
@Transactional
public void createOrder() {
    // Deduct inventory
    inventoryService.deductInventory(productId, 10); // Success
    
    // Try to save order with duplicate ID
    Order order = new Order();
    order.setId(existingId); // Duplicate!
    orderRepository.save(order); // Throws exception
    
    // Transaction rolls back
    // Inventory deduction is undone
}
```

**Result:** Inventory quantity restored to original value

---

### Scenario 3: Runtime Exception

```java
@Transactional
public void createOrder() {
    // Deduct inventory
    inventoryService.deductInventory(productId, 10); // Success
    
    // Business logic error
    if (customer.getBalance() < order.getTotal()) {
        throw new InsufficientFundsException(); // RuntimeException
    }
    
    // Transaction rolls back
    // Inventory deduction is undone
}
```

**Result:** All changes rolled back, including inventory

